{{infobox military structure |name = Fort de Vaujours |native_name = |partof = [[Fortifications of Paris in the 19th and 20th centuries|Fortifications of Paris, Séré de Rivières system]] |location = [[Courtry]], [[France]] |image = plan fortifications place de Paris.JPG |caption = German World War I postcard, showing the defenses of Paris |map_type = France Paris and inner ring |map_size = 300 |map_alt = |map_caption = |type = Fort |coordinates = {{coord|48.92555|2.59819|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |code = |built = {{Start date|1876}} |builder = |materials = Masonry, concrete |height = |used = |demolished = |condition = |ownership = French Atomic Energy Commission (closed) |open_to_public = No |controlledby = France |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }}
The '''Fort de Vaujours''', located in the commune of [[Courtry]], [[Seine-Saint-Denis]], near the town of [[Vaujours]], is one of the forts built at the end of the 19th century to defend [[Paris]]. It became a research center for the [[Commissariat à l'énergie atomique]] (CEA), France's Atomic Energy Commission. The center was closed in 1997.
==History== In 1870, France was partly occupied by the [[Prussia|Prussian army]]. As a result of this defeat, the [[Séré de Rivières system]] of fortifications was built from 1874–1881 to defend Paris, consisting of 18 forts, five redoubts and 34 batteries.
Construction started in 1876 on a roughly pentagonal fort with 48 artillery pieces and a garrison of 691 troops. Work was completed in 1882. The fort was updated in 1911 with a machine gun turret and a [[Mougin turret]] with two 155mm guns. The Fort de Vaujours is unique in its association with two annexes connected by a covered way to the main fort.<ref name="fortiffbe0">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/iff/index.php?page=10547|title=Vaujours (fort de)|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean |author2=Aublet, Jean-Louis |author3=Mainguin, Sylvie|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>
The fort's barracks were burned in 1944. In 1947 the Sevran explosives works used the facility. From 1955 the site was occupied by the CEA as a research center,<ref name="natact1">{{cite journal|year=2000|title=Le Centre d'Etudes Atomiques de Vaujours|journal=Nature Actualités|issue=80-81|language=French|url=http://www.asmsn.org/ancien_site/Risq%20ind/Vaujours.htm}}</ref> which considerably modified the fort and its environs. The CEA conducted pyrotechnic experiments at the location, using shock tubes and similar apparatus to study high-pressure shock waves in [[uranium]].<ref name="nwdb5">{{cite book|last=Norris|first=Robert S.|title=Nuclear Weapons Databook: Vol. V, British, French and Chinese Nuclear Weapons|year=1994|publisher=Westview Press/Natural Resources Defense Council|isbn=0-8133-1612-X|author2=Burrows, Andrew S. |author3=Fieldhouse, Richard W. |page=200}}</ref> The Vaujours facility closed in 1997. The CEA proposed to sell the property, but concerns about radioactive contamination have stalled the sale.<ref name="dissmedia1">{{cite news|url=http://www.dissident-media.org/infonucleaire/vaujours.html|title=Fort de Vaujours|last=Cordillot|first=Gilles|publisher=le Parisien|language=French|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>
The large trapeziodal fort's main armament was a twin 155mm [[Mougin turret]].<ref name="fortiffbe0"/> The turret remains, but its guns have been removed.<ref name="fortiffbe1">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/iff/index.php?page=intro10|title=Les tourelles curiassées Mle 1876 du commandant Mougin1|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean |author2=Aublet, Jean-Louis |author3=Mainguin, Sylvie|year=2010|work=Index de la fortification française 1874-1914|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="fortiff1">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiffsere.fr/index_fichiers/Page1585.htm|title=Implantation des tourelles Mougin|last=Vauborg|first=Cédric|author2=Vauborg, Julie|year=2010|publisher=Fortiff' Séré|language=French|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>
==Annexes== Fort de Vaujours' artillery battery annexes are located to the north and south of the main fort, connected by covered ways. The northern battery was manned by 162 troops with six gun mounts in casemates. The fort formed a rectangle, surrounded by a ditch which lacked the [[caponier]]s of the main fort for its defense. The south annex also has six gun emplacements. The north battery is being demolished while the south battery is in very good state and occupied by an association.<ref name="« fortiffbe2 »">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/iff/index.php?page=1053|title=Vaujours )batteries de)|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean |author2=Aublet, Jean-Louis |author3=Mainguin, Sylvie|year=2010|work=Index de la fortification française 1874-1914|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>
